---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Katie Kurtz — Kurtz Interiors | Heat & Glo Architects" description="Katie Kurtz of Kurtz Interiors specifies Heat & Glo 6K and 8K Series for traditional and transitional residential projects where the fireplace is the room's lasting anchor." noIndex={true}>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section style="position:relative; min-height:520px; display:flex; align-items:flex-end; overflow:hidden;">
    <img
      src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/0952f02a-9215-4865-bdeb-bb16f8dc1471/HNG_6-8000C_ChateauForge_Hammered"
      alt="Heat & Glo 6000C traditional gas fireplace with Chateau Forge hammered front — the anchor of a classic residential interior"
      style="position:absolute; inset:0; width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover; object-position:center;"
      loading="eager"
    />
    <div style="position:absolute; inset:0; background:linear-gradient(to top, rgba(18,12,8,0.85) 0%, rgba(18,12,8,0.44) 55%, rgba(18,12,8,0.12) 100%);"></div>
    <div style="position:relative; max-width:820px; padding:3rem 2rem; color:#fff;">
      <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.14em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#e8c998; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Designer Feature</p>
      <h1 style="font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem); font-weight:800; line-height:1.1; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Katie Kurtz</h1>
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:400; opacity:0.9; margin:0;">Kurtz Interiors &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Traditional and Transitional Residential</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main style="max-width:860px; margin:0 auto; padding:3rem 1.5rem;">

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Timeless Without Being Dated</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Traditional and transitional residential design is the segment of the market that produces the most permanent decisions. Contemporary interiors can be updated with paint and new furniture. Traditional interiors are built at a heavier material scale: millwork, stone, wood paneling, classical proportion. When you change your mind in one of these rooms, you are not rearranging accessories. You are undertaking a renovation.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Katie Kurtz built Kurtz Interiors on the conviction that this permanence is not a burden; it is a privilege. A well-designed traditional or transitional room should look correct in the year it is completed and in the decade after that. Not frozen in time, but grounded in it. The fireplace, which carries more visual mass and more material commitment than any other element in the room, is where that principle lives most concretely.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        Katie's aesthetic vocabulary moves between fully classical interior environments, rooms with applied molding profiles, symmetrically disposed built-ins, and traditional furniture scale, and the broader category of transitional design, where classical proportion is retained but applied ornament is simplified and contemporary materials appear alongside traditional ones. The fireplace specification must work in both registers without creating a visible seam between the unit and the surround that surrounds it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- PULL QUOTE -->
    <section style="border-left:4px solid #7a5c2a; padding:1.25rem 1.75rem; background:#faf6ef; margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; line-height:1.7; color:#2a2a2a; font-style:italic; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
        "My clients are not decorating their house. They are building their home. Those are different things. The fireplace in a traditional room has to feel like it belongs to the architecture of the building, not like it was specified from a catalog. The 6K Series gives me the depth and the proportion to make that read happen. Ten years from now, it still looks like the right decision."
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:0.8125rem; color:#6b6b6b; margin:0; font-style:normal; letter-spacing:0.04em; text-transform:uppercase;">Paraphrased from Katie Kurtz's ProAdvantage program onboarding &mdash; illustrative, not a verified direct quotation</p>
    </section>

    <!-- WHY HEAT & GLO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Why Kurtz Interiors Specifies Heat &amp; Glo</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        The 6K and 8K Series are Katie's primary specification tools in traditional and transitional residential contexts because their firebox proportions and flame presentation are calibrated for the visual grammar of these interior types. In a room with a substantial timber or stone mantel, a full-height overmantel, and furniture arranged in the classical layout that orients seating toward the hearth as the primary room event, the firebox face and flame character need to read with appropriate weight. A shallow, horizontally proportioned linear flame does not read correctly in this context. The 6K and 8K Series have the vertical depth and the layered flame profile that fulfill the expectation a traditional surround establishes.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        In transitional work, Katie's preference for the True Series emerges. The True occupies a middle register: it has the traditional firebox proportion and flame depth that a transitional room requires without the fully classical visual weight of the 6K configuration. For a transitional living room where the mantel is clean-lined and the palette is warm-neutral rather than richly patterned, the True reads correctly and, critically, it reads correctly across the full life of the room as the client's material and furniture choices evolve.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        Katie's clients frequently ask about gas versus wood-burning options. Her consistent response is that gas, specified well, satisfies the visual and thermal experience that drives the desire for a fireplace without introducing the operational complexity, maintenance requirements, and air quality considerations that a wood-burning system brings. The Heat and Glo flame realism in the 6K and 8K lines is a significant part of that conversation. When the flame looks right, the objection dissolves.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- TYPICAL PROJECT SHAPE -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">The Shape of a Kurtz Interiors Project</h2>
      <h3 style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:600; color:#7a5c2a; margin:0 0 1rem;">When the Room Is Built to Last</h3>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        A typical Kurtz Interiors engagement is a primary residence where the clients have decided to invest at a level that reflects permanence. They are not staging a home for resale. They are building an environment for their family and their life. That orientation shapes every material decision in the project, and it shapes the fireplace conversation in a particular way: durability, visual correctness, and the ability to live with the decision gracefully over time become more important than novelty or trend alignment.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Katie's traditional projects often involve rooms with significant millwork: built-in bookshelves flanking the fireplace, an overmantel with applied molding, or a fireplace wall that reads as architectural cabinetry. The Heat and Glo units that appear in these installations need to be specified for their face dimensions and clearance requirements early in the design development phase, because the millwork package is typically custom-built to the fireplace rough opening. Changes after millwork construction begins are expensive and disruptive. Katie's working relationship with the ProAdvantage program supports early submittal and clearance documentation that makes the millwork fabrication timeline possible.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        On the transitional side, Kurtz Interiors projects tend to include clients who are making a design shift from a more traditional context they grew up in toward a slightly lighter, more contemporary-adjacent vocabulary. The fireplace is often the element where that shift is negotiated most carefully. Katie's skill in the transitional register comes from her ability to honor the client's attachment to traditional warmth while introducing the material simplification and proportion adjustment that distinguishes transitional from dated. The Heat and Glo True and 6K families give her product options at both ends of that negotiation.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 1 -->
    <section style="background:#1a1a1a; color:#fff; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#e8c998; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Trade Program</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Join ProAdvantage</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; opacity:0.8; margin:0;">Dedicated trade support, priority access, and project resources for design professionals working in traditional and transitional residential.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/pro/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Explore ProAdvantage</a>
    </section>

    <!-- INSTALLATION CARDS -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1.5rem;">Sample Installations in the Kurtz Register</h2>
      <div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(240px,1fr)); gap:1.5rem;">

        <!-- Card 1 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/5b7a314a-1bbb-4944-a964-2530fcd0ff0b/HNG_Exclaim_MasonryBrn_TradBrick_HeritageOak"
              alt="Heat & Glo Exclaim with masonry brown traditional brick firebox and heritage oak log set — the traditional great room specification"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">True Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Traditional Great Room</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Stone hearth, flanking built-in shelving, symmetrically disposed seating. The traditional great room that looks correct the day it is built and ten years after.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 2 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/06252566-e202-4816-a3f2-8a3c9d62dfd1/23_HHT_Birmingham_Rutherford_Ashland_BlkHerr_3Tier_GrandBirch_Room"
              alt="Heat & Glo Birmingham with Rutherford Ashland black herringbone interior and 3-tier Grand Birch log set in a transitional family room"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">6K Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Transitional Family Room</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">A warm, lived-in family room where the fireplace anchors daily life. Traditional proportion, simplified surround, a room built for the long term.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 3 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/27f4b679-bc2f-42f8-b949-56a3aaba3f3e/25_HHT_Birmingham_Rutherford_Ashland_AntlerVelvetHerr_3Tier_HeritageOak_Indoor"
              alt="Heat & Glo Birmingham with antler velvet herringbone interior and heritage oak 3-tier log set — the full traditional-to-transitional range"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">6K / 8K / True Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Traditional to Transitional Range</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">The Heat and Glo lineup that Kurtz Interiors draws on across the traditional-to-transitional spectrum. One brand relationship, the full range of client needs.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 2 -->
    <section style="background:#faf6ef; border:1px solid #ddd0b8; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#7a5c2a; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Dealer Network</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Find a Local Dealer</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Connect with a Heat and Glo dealer for traditional fireplace spec sheets, millwork clearance documentation, and showroom access near your project.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/where-to-buy/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Dealer Locator</a>
    </section>

    <p style="color:#888; font-size:0.875rem; border-top:1px solid #e5e0db; padding-top:1.5rem;"><a href="/architect/" style="color:#c44a08; text-decoration:none;">Back to all architects</a></p>
  </main>

</BaseLayout>
